@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{toori ni}}" grammar="@HI{{toori ni}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{toori ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{toori ni}}}},
<li> @Vta{{}} @EM{{@HI{{toori ni}}}},
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} @EM{{@HI{{toori ni}}}},
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
These sentence patterns mean to copy exactly in words or actions whatever V describes.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ga yaru @EM{{toori ni}}, yatte kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please do as I do.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{see}}ta@EM{{toori ni}}, @KJ{{tale}}shite kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please tell us what you saw as it was.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{line}}no@EM{{toori ni}}, @KJ{{paper}}wo@KJ{{cut}}tte kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please cut the paper folowing the line.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The dictionary form is used when the action is going to be performed from now and the @HI{{ta}}-form is used
when the action has already been performed.
</p>

<h2> References </h2>

<ol>
<li> @REF{{MNN-TR-II}}. (Chapter 34).
</ol>

